;</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody">On Thu, Jul 15, 2010 at 9:44 AM, Mathieu Desnoyers<br />&lt;mathieu.desnoyers&#64;efficios.com&gt; wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; The first thing that strikes me is that we could be interrupted by a standard<br />&gt; interrupt on top of the iret instruction below.<br /><br />No, that can never happen.<br /><br />Why? Simple: regular interrupts aren't ever enabled in eflags. So the<br />only kinds of traps we can get are NMI's (that don't follow the normal<br />rules), and exceptions.<br /><br />Of course, if there is some trap that re-enables interrupts even if<br />the trap happened in an interrupt-disabled region, then that would<br />change things, but that would be a bad bug regardless (and totally<br />independently of any NMI issues). So in that sense it's a "could<br />happen", but it's something that would be a totally separate bug.<br /><br />                    Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
